XXIII. These cases may occur: that punishment may require absolutely to be exacted, as in crimes of very bad example 3—or may be fit not to be exactcd, as if the public good require it to be omit- ted ;—or either course may be allowable: when, as Seneca says, Cle- nzency has free will. Then, say the Stoics, the wise man spares, but does not pardon: as if we might not, with common usage, call that par- don, which they call spariny. In fact here and elsewhere, as Cicero, Galen and others have noted, a great part of the disputations of the Stoics is about words, which a philosopher ought carefully to avoid. So the writer to Herennius and Aristotle say.
